Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450}(chopped into 2cm chunks) and place in a large #mixing bowl{}. Add the @ground turmeric{2}, @nigella seeds{1}, a glug of @oil{} and a large pinch of @salt{pinch} and toss to combine. Transfer to a #baking tray{} and roast on the top shelf of your oven until so and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Peel and grate the garlic (or use a #garlic press{}). Pop the @lamb mince{200} in another mixing bowl with the @North Indian style spice mix{1}(use less if you don't like spice). Add a pinch of @salt{pinch}, the shallot and half the garlic. Mix well and use wet hands to shape the mix into one patty per person, 2cm thick. Keep to one side.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Pick the @mint{½}(leaves picked from stalks and finely chopped) and finely chop (discard the stalks). Place in a #small bowl{}. Stir in the remaining garlic, the @Greek style natural yoghurt{150} and more @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Mix well then taste and add a pinch of salt and pepper if needed.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Fry the burgers until nicely caramelised on both sides, turning every couple of minutes, ~{15-17%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The burgers are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Cut the @burger buns{2} in half and pop them on another baking tray on the middle shelf of your oven for a few mins to warm through. Smear a generous dollop of mint yoghurt on the bottom half of the bun and place the burger on. Pop a few @wild rocket{40} leaves on top and then finish with the other half of the bun.

When the roasties are ready, remove from the oven and serve alongside the burger, with any leftover rocket and a good dollop of mint yoghurt to dip your roasties in. Enjoy!